    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the Management’s Discussion and Analysis (MD&A) sections provided, here is what the filing conveys about capital expenditure trends, plans, and the composition of construction-in-progress.\n\n### Capital Expenditure Historical Trends and Commentary from the MD&A\n\nThe MD&A includes a table of capital expenditures by segment and a narrative explanation of year-over-year changes:\n\n**Capital Expenditures by Segment (in millions)**\n\n| Segment | Q1 2026 | Q1 2025 | FY2025 | FY2024 | FY2023 |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| Space | $1,052 | $759 | $3,832 | $2,032 | $1,497 |\n| Connectivity | 1,332 | 814 | 4,178 | 3,498 | 2,455 |\n| AI | 7,723 | 2,567 | 12,727 | 5,633 | 463 |\n| **Total** | **$10,107** | **$4,140** | **$20,737** | **$11,163** | **$4,415** |\n\nThe MD&A then provides the following details on historical changes:\n\n*   **Space Segment:** The Q1 2026 increase of $293 million versus Q1 2025, the FY2025 increase of $1.8 billion versus FY2024, and the FY2024 increase of $535 million versus FY2023 were all “primarily driven by increased investment in our launch site infrastructure for Starship.”\n*   **Connectivity Segment:** The Q1 2026 increase of $518 million versus Q1 2025, the FY2025 increase of $680 million versus FY2024, and the FY2024 increase of $1.043 billion versus FY2023 were all “primarily driven by higher satellite and ground equipment costs as we continue to increase our number of satellites and grow our satellite network.”\n*   **AI Segment:** The Q1 2026 increase of $5.156 billion versus Q1 2025, the FY2025 increase of $7.094 billion versus FY2024, and the FY2024 increase of $5.17 billion versus FY2023 were all “primarily driven by investments in the rapid expansion of our terrestrial data centers, including the development, construction, and equipping of new facilities and supporting infrastructure.”\n\n### Forward-Looking Plans Discussed in the MD&A\n\nThe MD&A also contains sections that, while not labeled “capital expenditure plans,” clearly outline the strategic investments driving future spending:\n\n*   **Starship Development:** A dedicated subsection entitled “Developing Starship” states that Starship is “central to our goal of unlocking growth” and that the company expects it to be the only fully reusable two-stage vehicle. It notes that Starship’s deployment will “dramatically expand our launch capability” and is expected to “establish a scalable path to creating the infrastructure of the future, such as orbital AI compute.” This implies continued significant investment in the launch site infrastructure already cited as the driver of Space segment capex growth.\n*   **AI Infrastructure:** The narrative repeatedly emphasizes that the “rapid expansion of our terrestrial data centers” is the primary driver of surging AI capital expenditures. This is presented as an ongoing and core investment theme, not a one-time event.\n\n### Construction-in-Progress (CIP) Balance Detail and Segment Association\n\nThe most recent balance sheet detail for CIP comes from **Note 5 (Property, Plant, and Equipment, Net)** . The note discloses the gross CIP balance but does not break it down by segment. The figures are:\n\n*   **March 31, 2026:** $14,045 million\n*   **December 31, 2025:** $4,604 million\n\nThe associated footnote text explains the general composition of the CIP balance:\n> “Construction in progress is primarily comprised of ongoing construction and expansion of the facilities and equipment as well as AI infrastructure that has not yet been placed in service.”\n\n**How much CIP is associated with AI infrastructure vs. other segments?**\nThe filing does **not** provide a quantitative split of the $14.0 billion CIP balance between AI, Space, and Connectivity. However, a strong inference can be drawn from the MD&A’s capital expenditure trends:\n\n*   **AI is the dominant driver:** Total capital expenditures in the AI segment were $7.7 billion in Q1 2026 alone, and the CIP balance increased by $9.4 billion during the same quarter ($14.0 billion vs. $4.6 billion). The text explicitly states that AI capex is for “data centers... development, construction, and equipping” and that CIP is “primarily” for *both* “facilities and equipment” and “AI infrastructure.” Given the financial magnitudes, the vast majority of the $14.0 billion CIP balance, and nearly all of the $9.4 billion sequential increase, is almost certainly related to AI data center construction.\n*   **Other segments also contribute:** The MD&A does not state that the CIP is *exclusively* AI, and the footnote mentions “ongoing construction and expansion of the facilities and equipment” broadly. The continuing investments in Starship launch site infrastructure and satellite/ground equipment likely account for a smaller portion of the CIP balance for Space and Connectivity, respectively.',
